@* LINQ aggregates (BENCH n°40, decision 121): the number aggregates over a List map to JS array reductions --
   Sum -> reduce((a,b)=>a+b,0), Min/Max -> Math.min/max(...arr), Average -> sum/length, First/Last -> index.
   #go computes the Sum of the elements > 3 and the Max of [3,7,2,9,5]: Sum(7+9+5)=21, Max=9. So #sum goes
   "0" -> "21" and #max "0" -> "9", exactly as Blazor runs the same C# LINQ. No runtime primitive is added. total
   and peak are read by @total/@peak AND assigned by Go -> signals; _nums is never mutated -> a plain array. *@

<p>Sum: <span id="sum">@total</span>, Max: <span id="max">@peak</span></p>

<button id="go" @onclick="Go">go</button>

@code {
    private int total = 0;
    private int peak = 0;
    private System.Collections.Generic.List<int> _nums = new System.Collections.Generic.List<int> { 3, 7, 2, 9, 5 };

    private void Go()
    {
        total = _nums.Where(x => x > 3).Sum();
        peak = _nums.Max();
    }
}
